\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b a}) Subsp.{\b  maritima }({\i C. maritima} subsp.{\i  integrifolia} (Hornem.) Hyl.): Leaves subentire to pinnatisect, the primary segments not more than 5 times as long as wide. Pedicels 1·5-5(-7) mm in fruit. Lower segment of the silicula flat (when viewed in the plane of the projections) and convex (when viewed in the plane at right-angles to the projections); projections usually less than 0·5 mm, sometimes obscure. Upper segment of the silicula expanding into a membranous margin at the base. 2n = 18. {\i W. & N.W. Europe from C. Portugal to c.} 68°{\i  N. in Norway; rarely in the Baltic and Mediterranean regions in the vicinity of ports, where it is probably introduced}.
\par

\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b b}) Subsp{\b . euxina} (Pobed.) E.I. Nyárády in Savul.,{\i  Fl. Rep. Pop. Române}{\b  3}: 480 (1955) ({\i C. euxina }Pobed.): Leaves 1- or 2-pinnatisect, the primary segments up to 15 times as long as wide. Pedicels 2-4·5 mm in fruit. Lower segment of the silicula more or less concave at the apex (when viewed in the plane of the projections), with projections usually less than 0·5 mm; articulating surface with 2 erect triangular teeth. Upper segment of the silicula expanding into a membranous margin at the base. 2n = 18.{\i  Black Sea region}.
\par

\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b c}) Subsp.{\b  baltica} (Jordan ex Rouy & Fouc.) Hyl. ex P.W. Ball,{\i  Feddes Repert.}{\b  69}: 37 (1964) ({\i C. baltica} Jordan ex Pobed.): Like ({\b b}) but primary leaf segments 10-20 times as long as wide; pedicels 3-5 mm in fruit; lower segment of the silicula not concave at the apex, with deflexed projections usually exceeding 1 mm; articulating surface without erect teeth. 2n = 18. {\i Baltic region and S.E. Norway}.
\par

\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b d}) Subsp.{\b  aegyptiaca} (Willd.) Nyman,{\i  Consp.} 29 (1878): Leaves subentire to pinnatisect, the primary divisions rarely more than 6 times as long as wide. Pedicels 1·5-6 mm in fruit. Lower segment of the silicula more or less concave at the apex (when viewed in the plane of the projections), with deflexed projections usually exceeding 0·5 mm; articulating surface sometimes with 2 erect triangular teeth. Upper segment of the silicula expanding into a membranous margin at the base. 2n = 18.{\i  Mediterranean region and S. Portugal}.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Populations in the Aegean region are mostly intermediate between subspp. ({\b b}) and ({\b d}).
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Subsp. ({\b d}) is not always clearly distinct from subsp. ({\b a}) on the basis of the fruit characters given above. However, these subspecies are apparently distinct phytochemically (J.E. Rodman,{\i  Syst. Bot.}{\b 1}:137-148 (1976)), and in nectary structure (M. Clemente & J.E. Hernández-Bermejo,{\i  Anal. Inst. Bot. Cavanilles}{\b  35}: 279-296 (1978)). The situation is further complicated by the occurrence of plants apparently identical with ({\b a}) in the vicinity of ports in the Mediterranean region.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 In subsp. ({\b a}) the lower segment of the silicula is often sterile, and resembles an extension of the pedicel.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Plants in which the apex of the lower segment of the silicula is flat, without projections, and in which the upper segment is contracted to a flat base without a membranous margin, have been referred to {\b C. edentula} subsp.{\b  islandica} (Gand.) Á. & D. Löve, Bot. Not. {\b 114}: 52 (1961) ({\i C. arctica} Pobed.,{\i  C. lapponica} Pobed.), but may justify recognition as a fifth subsp. of{\i  C. maritima.} Reported from N. Russia, N. Norway, Svalbard, Faeröer and Iceland, intermediates between it and subsp. ({\b a}) are frequent in N. Norway between 66° N. and 68° N.
\par

